<subSubSection id="2564171606597A5F10DC43A61A3D4D3C" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" type="notes">
<paragraph id="3B1F6E956497AE33CEA010CDB9010084" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9A7B885A32F7BD890D4EF4FF314B8E42" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997">
Frequently reported from Greece, considered cosmopolitan (
<bibRefCitation id="0878A1CD8CBF26B4988DC52DCA42992B" author="Pleijel, Fredrik" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Natural History" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" pagination="2547 - 2566" title="A revision of Hesiospina (Psamathini, Hesionidae, Polychaeta)" volume="38" year="2004">Pleijel 2004</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="A122640DDE82CEAA734C501055D7710A" author="Simboura, Nomiki" journalOrPublisher="PhD thesis. National and Kapodistrian University of Athens, Athens" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" title="Θαλάσσοι μακροβενθικοί Πολύxαιτοι (AnnelidaPolychaeta) της Ελλάδας: Συστηματική, Οικολογία, Ζωογεωγραφία" year="1996">Simboura (1996)</bibRefCitation>
notes morphological differences between specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="17618BF358B8DA9ACBE4DC8F12408E4B" class="Polychaeta" family="Hesionidae" genus="Hesiospina" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hesiospina similis" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="similis">Hesiospina similis</taxonomicName>
from the Mediterranean and from the native range (Japan). Specifically, Mediterranean material exhibits a stronger serration of the blades of the compound chaetae and neuropodial aciculae with rounded instead of tapering tips.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
